  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The microbiome is variable between individuals and time.",
    "This biological variability can make it challenging to identify universal patterns or develop generalizable models (Kodikara et al., 2022; Vinciotti et al., 2023).",
    "Also, the taxonomic and functional variability of microbial communities can exhibit significant differences across different environments, making it difficult to establish consistent associations.",
    "Complex machine learning models, such as deep neural networks, might lack interpretability, making it challenging to understand the biological significance of the learned patterns as these models may not be able to generalize to new, unseen data (Linardatos et al., 2021).",
    "Interpretable models are often preferred in microbiome research to gain insights into the relationships between microbial features and expected outcomes (Bengtsson-Palme, 2020)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "This biological variability can make it challenging to identify universal patterns or develop generalizable models (Kodikara et al., 2022; Vinciotti et al., 2023).",
